Based on the provided documents, IBM Cloudant Query is an API for querying slices of data based on the values of a database's document attributes. It is accessed through the [POST /{db}/_find](https://cloud.ibm.com/apidocs/cloudantpostfind) API endpoint where the JSON specification of the query is passed in the HTTP POST body. For example, this query finds up to 10 documents where the `firstname` is "Charles" and the `surname` is "Dickens":
```json
{
  "selector": {
    "firstname": "Charles",
    "surname": "Dickens"
  },
  "limit": 10
}
```
To create an index to support an IBM Cloudant Query, you can call the [POST /{db}/_index](https://cloud.ibm.com/apidocs/cloudantpostindex) endpoint to pass the JSON index definition as the HTTP POST body. For example, to create an index for the `firstname` and `surname` fields, you can use the following JSON index definition:
```json
{
  "index": {
    "fields": ["firstname", "surname"]
  },
  "ddoc": "jsonindexes"
}
```
If you need to access objects within documents, you can use standard dot notation for example, `address.zipcode` to access a postal code string inside an `address` object. Additionally, you can specify the `fields`, `sort`, and `limit` parameters to define the document attributes you want returned, how the data is to be sorted, and the number of documents to return.

If you are from a relational database background, you can think of the `WHERE` clause as the equivalent of the `selector` in IBM Cloudant Query, `ORDER` as the equivalent of `sort`, and `LIMIT` as the equivalent of `limit`. The IBM Cloudant Query `FIELDS` list is equivalent to the comma-separated list of attributes after the `SELECT` keyword in an SQL query.
